<div ana="#b1" corresp="#abil0001.translation" subtype="transcription" type="edition" xml:id="abil0001.diplomatic" xml:lang="heb">
<p>דכיר ל<supplied reason="undefined">ט</supplied>
<gap reason="illegible"/>
<supplied reason="undefined">ב</supplied>ר<gap reason="illegible"/>
<supplied reason="undefined">ך</supplied>
<lb/>
<gap reason="illegible"/>
<unclear>סד</unclear>ריי דהכה<lb/>
<supplied reason="lost">ד</supplied>אתחזק<lb/>
<supplied reason="lost">ב</supplied>דין תרעה<lb/> שלום</p>
</div>
<div ana="#b1" corresp="#abil0001.diplomatic" type="translation" xml:id="abil0001.translation">
<p>Remember for good Baruch [?] of Alexandria [?] who here gave and made this gate.
                    Amen, peace.</p>
</div>
</body>
<back>
<div type="commentary">
<p>The inscription was engraved on a cross-bar stone and discovered in a narrow street facing the church, which is located in the southern part of the village. The inscription and surrounding figures were found on the part of the stone that faces the street. There is a fracture at the top of the stone, which makes the beginning of the inscription difficult to read and required Barslavsky to fill in the blanks. The first line includes a well-known phrase which Barslavsky could easily recognize as "דכיר לטב" even though the ט and the ב were destroyed completely.</p>
</div>
